{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1724b203-0688-42b3-858a-262e0e16435d","content":"Here's how to set up **NuGet Trusted Publishing** using GitHub Actions OIDC — no API keys needed.\n\n## Two steps required:\n\n### 1. Register on nuget.org\n\nGo to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → (your package) → Trusted Publishers** and add:\n\n| Field | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Repository owner | `myorg` |\n| Repository | `mylib` |\n| Workflow file | `publish.yml` |\n| Environment | `nuget` |\n\n*(If the package doesn't exist yet, register it first or use \"Register new package with trusted publisher\".)*\n\n### 2. Create the GitHub Actions workflow","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_yvXzUPcJhUovWDQYfDEKOy","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating NuGet publish workflow"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_7wYLR9MuvqZAFHDKS6ZxRi","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-84f0dbbc345e437dbb9c65d2c9d20733/.github/workflows","description":"Create workflows directory"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflows directory"}],"interactionId":"0b8b6809-4fbd-4a60-8a09-b609952d8a56","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to set up secure NuGet publishing from GitHub Actions using trusted publishing (without API keys). This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code task. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nThe modern approach is to use NuGet's trusted publishing with OIDC tokens, which was introduced in 2023-2024. Let me explain the setup.\n\nActually, let me think about what the current best practice is as of 2026:\n\n1. **NuGet Trusted Publishers** - NuGet.org supports OIDC-based trusted publishing from GitHub Actions, similar to PyPI's trusted publishers. This eliminates the need for API keys.\n\n\n2. The workflow involves registering your GitHub repository as a trusted publisher on NuGet.org, then using the OIDC token that GitHub Actions provides to authenticate the `dotnet nuget push` command. I should walk through both the NuGet.org configuration and the GitHub Actions workflow setup to make this actionable. I'll structure this with both the nuget.org configuration steps and a complete GitHub Actions workflow example so they can implement this end-to-end.","outputTokens":854,"requestId":"E3EF:86E8:1C8E7AD:2012AF3:6A07C01C"},"id":"3ccfe7ea-4f6b-406a-af74-31f0068b45d4","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:54:07.341Z","parentId":"9d205d82-0b99-4cc5-a5b9-a79594027c56"}
